snippet.textDisplay:
Christmas movie idea:


Santa is actually an indigenous person who used to deliver presents, but when people tried to come to the North Pole and colonize his land, he enslaved all their children. He no longer delivers presents to anybody who are descendants of colonizers. Instead parents pretended that Santa gave their kids presents until eventually the world stopped believing that he was real. The holiday has become a whitewashed Christian tradition meaning Santa failed in punishing the colonizers.


Until one year... Santa decides to take back his holiday. He takes his army of "elves" and slowly starts to take over major cities. Eventually he gains control over the most powerful countries on the world. With his influence, he manages to pass a worldwide law that makes it illegal to celebrate Christmas. Anything Christmas related is banned; songs, movies, decorations, foods, all of it. Instead everyone has to celebrate Indigenous People's Day (previously known as Columbus Day, an American holiday recently rebranded). On this day, everyone has to give gifts to the indigenous people of their country and Santa gives out luxurious gifts to indigenous tribes.


Then a revolution begins! People are mad because they did not colonize! their ancestors were the culprits, not them! The hold protests and struggle to have their governments hear them out, but Santa does not want to listen. He needs revenge for the holiday he loved so much being ripped away from him. It isn't until he witnesses a true tragedy that he understands where he went wrong. An elementary school segregated full of "colonizer" children is blown up after there is suspicion of a rebel force operating from inside. There wasn't.


After the tragedy, Santa realizes how he has become his worst nightmare. He has let revenge consume him. He became a colonizer. He decides to reinstate Christmas, desegregate the countries, and release his "elves". He opens up a toy factory where he pays good money and twice a year he donates toys to charities on Indigenous Peoples Day (still celebrated worldwide as a present exchanging holiday) and Christmas.


THE END


Has this been made yet? If so, let me know so I can watch it.
